actual flow for a command like `run: \"go test ./...\"`, the issue is that `readScriptFromCommand` is iterating through the command tokens and accidentally finding a `test` file in the directory, then reading it as binary content. After the fix, I need to ensure it properly filters to only `.cloche/scripts/` files and skips over unrelated files in the working directory.\n\nThe real question is what the frontend should do when there's no actual script content to display—whether hiding the content panel makes sense when we're just showing the raw command text, or if that text is valuable enough to keep visible. the command text is already displayed in the drawer metadata, so showing it again in the content panel would be redundant. I should focus on two fixes: prevent the backend from loading binary or non-script files through `readScriptFromCommand`, and hide the content panel on the frontend when the API returns empty content. the content panel when there's nothing to display. So the implementation is straightforward: the backend returns 204 No Content when the script file doesn't exist or isn't readable, and the frontend hides the content panel accordingly. the `run` value itself isn't useful without context, so I should just return empty. Let me start coding the backend changes now. Writing the handler logic...\n\nActually, I'm realizing this changes the behavior for all `run` configs—previously bare commands like `bash .cloche/scripts/foo.sh arg1` would load their script content, but now only scripts directly under `.cloche/scripts/` get loaded, so commands referencing scripts elsewhere won't show their content anymore.\n\nThat aligns with the task requirements though—scripts outside `.cloche/scripts/` shouldn't be loaded. I'm also thinking through the HTTP status code change: returning 204 instead of the command text means the frontend gets an empty response, which triggers the \"No content available\" message, effectively hiding the content panel as intended.\n\nI need to update the frontend to handle this properly—checking for the 204 status and hiding the content div when there's no text to display. I should also make sure the display gets reset when opening a new drawer, though I'm realizing the content element might be created dynamically in the body.\n\nLooking at how the drawer-content div is being generated, it's recreated fresh each time, so I can just hide it when there's no content. I'll go with setting `display: 'none'` since it's straightforward and clear.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the HTTP status code approach—204 No Content is semantically correct since the server processed the request successfully but has nothing to return, though I need to be careful about how clients handle it. With 204, `response.text()` returns an empty string in browsers, and since I'm checking `r.ok && r.status !== 204` before calling `r.text()`, the ternary will return that empty string appropriately.\n\nActually, returning a plain 200 with an empty body might be simpler—the frontend can just check if the text is empty and hide the element accordingly. The current code already handles empty responses from `resolveFileRef`, so this approach would be consistent with existing behavior. I need to handle the Content-Type header that's already set before the config checks, which is fine for empty responses. Now I'm implementing the solution, including helper functions to detect whether data is text content by checking for null bytes, and handling cases where the `run` references a file outside the scripts directory or points to a binary.\n\nWriting handler code... Completing the file path logic and verifying the security check works correctly—if someone passes just \"go\" it won't match the scripts directory prefix, but \".cloche/scripts/setup.sh\" will, so the path validation is sound. The prefix check with the trailing separator handles this correctly—a file directly in `.cloche/scripts/` would be something like `.cloche/scripts/foo.sh